         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot &amp; zool. Garden ¶ 26. Nov. 1861 ¶ Dear Sir William. ¶  ¶ It was highly gratifying to me to learn from your kind letter, dated 26 Sept and also from Dr Hookers letter by the last mail, ¶  ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">61.11.26a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Directors' letters, vol. LXXV, Australian and Pacific Letters 1859-65, letter no. 139.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS black-edged; M's sister Bertha Doughty died on 7 September 1861. MS annotation: '[six illegible words] Paphp[phum]'.</p>
               </note>Melbourne bot &amp; zool. Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">26. Nov. 1861</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir William.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It was highly gratifying to me to learn from your kind letter, dated 26 Sept and also from Dr Hookers letter by the last mail,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>W. Hooker's letter not found; see J. Hooker to M, 22 September 1861.</p>
               </note> that my proposition in regard to Mr Benthams Flora had met with so cordial an acceptance from you and your celebrated son, and that you entertain the hope of Mr Bentham approving also of my propositions; I only await now Mr Benthams final answer to prepare for the shipment of the <name key="Thalamiflorae">Thalamiflorae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As I shall write more fully on the subject of the transmissions by next mail, I have little to add, but to express my joy of Dr Harvey's recovery. I truly hope, he will take care of himself, for how is such a man to be replaced if we loose him?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now nearly through the <name key="Thalamiflorae">Thalamiflorae</name>. It would have been done earlier but for the tragical calamities of the Exploring party!<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Burke &amp; Wills Exploring Expedition, 1860-1. The deaths of Robert O'Hara Burke, William James Wills and Charles Gray were reported in a despatch by A. W. Howitt dated 10 October 1861 and received by the Exploration Committee in Melbourne on 4 November 1861.</p>
               </note> A glorious achievement has come to the saddest termination! without direct fault of anyone here or in the field.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In examining the <name key="Geraniaceae">Geraniaceae</name>, I find that all Pelargonia have not convolute and twisted cotyledons as <name key="Geranium">Geranium</name>, but flat or slightly concave-convex cotyledons. Perhaps this important distinctive note is worthy of Dr Hookers acceptance for the genera plantarum. <name key="Howittia">Howittia</name> has trifid cotyledons. I have recently received male flowers of <name key="Gyrostemon%20cotinifolius">Gyrostemon cotinifolius</name>. The anthers are uniseriate thus it differs from the remaining typical <name key="Gyrostemon%20ramulosus">Gyrostemon ramulosus</name> and now I transfer it therefore together with my genus <name key="Hymenotheca">Hymenotheca</name> to <name key="Codonocarpus">Codonocarpus</name>,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The transfer was reported in B62.02.01, p. 200. M had erected the genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Hymenotheca">Hymenotheca</name>
                     </seg> in B59.12.01, 202.</p>
               </note> which we may presume to have the same anthereal arrangement. Dr Hooker will find in the now forwarded closing fascicle of the II vol of the fragmenta some note by Planchon, who draws <name key="Cadellia">Cadellia</name> near <name key="Biebersteinia">Biebersteinia</name>, <name key="Suriana">Suriana</name> &amp; <name key="Limnanthus">Limnanthus</name>.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B61.11.04, p. 171. M wrote 'Illustris Planchon hoc genus in viciniam Limnanthae <name key="Suriana">Suriana</name>e et <name key="Biebersteinia">Biebersteinia</name>e posuit' [<seg style="">The illustrious Planchon placed this genus in the neighborhood of Limnanthes, <name key="Suriana">Suriana</name> and <name key="Biebersteinia">Biebersteinia</name>]</seg>, but gave no authority for the claim. No publication by Planchon to this effect has been found; he may have made the comment in a letter.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If Dr Hooker could manage to send me through the despatch bag of the Governor or otherwise proofsheets of his &amp; Benth genera<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> by the mails, I would be able to furnish any additions in such time, as to be enrolled (if accepted) in the last pages of his volumes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is a source of deep gratification to my feelings, that I hear of your regaining health. Let me implore you to take the greatest care of yourself, my dear Sir William; — Extensive cessation of work during winter and enjoyment of the air of the rural districts in summer I feel sure will long retain for us the blessing of your being amongst us.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever your gratefully attached</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My kindest regards to Dr Hooker &amp; Mr Bentham; to both I will write by next mail.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr. Hooker will note that <name key="Rhytidandra">Rhytidandra</name> Asa Gr. belongs to <name key="Alangiaceae">Alangiaceae</name> &amp; that <name key="Pseudalangium">Pseudalangium</name> is the same genus.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Are seeds of <name key="Elymus%20geniculatus">Elymus geniculatus</name> readily in your noble establishment. Should this [<name key="Siphonia">Siphonia</name>] be new, perhaps the excellent Mr Berkely will name it in honor of the finder.</p>
